Risk Modeling Framework
Market Risk Analytics Dashboard using VaR, Monte Carlo Simulation & Stress Testing

A quantitative risk management framework built in Python for measuring and visualizing portfolio risk using real market data.

The project implements classical and simulation-based risk models including:

Historical Value at Risk (VaR)
Parametric VaR
Monte Carlo VaR
Expected Shortfall (CVaR)
Stress Testing
Historical Crisis Replay
Drawdown Analysis

The results are presented through an interactive Streamlit dashboard.

Project Overview

Risk management is a fundamental component of quantitative finance.

This project builds a complete risk analytics pipeline:

Market Data
     |
     ↓
Return Calculation
     |
     ↓
Portfolio Risk Engine
     |
     ↓
VaR / Expected Shortfall Models
     |
     ↓
Stress Testing
     |
     ↓
Interactive Dashboard

The goal is to simulate how a portfolio behaves under normal market conditions and extreme market events.

Features
1. Market Data Pipeline

The framework accepts historical price data:

data/raw/prices.csv

The pipeline calculates:

daily returns
portfolio returns
cumulative performance
Risk Metrics
Value at Risk (VaR)

VaR estimates the maximum expected loss over a given confidence level.

Example:

95% VaR = €1,500

means:

There is a 95% probability that the portfolio will not lose more than €1,500 in one day.

Implemented methods:

Historical Simulation VaR

Uses actual historical return observations.

Advantages:

no distribution assumptions
captures real market behavior
Parametric VaR

Assumes normally distributed returns:

R∼N(μ,σ
2
)

The risk measure is calculated using:

VaR=−z
α
	​

σ+μ
Monte Carlo VaR

Simulates thousands of possible future return scenarios.

Process:

Estimate return parameters
Generate random scenarios
Calculate simulated losses
Extract percentile loss

Example:

10,000 simulations
95% percentile loss
Expected Shortfall

Expected Shortfall measures the average loss beyond the VaR threshold.

Formula:

ES=E[X∣X>VaR]

Unlike VaR, Expected Shortfall captures tail risk.

Stress Testing

The framework includes hypothetical market shocks:

Examples:

Scenario	Shock
Market Correction	-10%
Severe Crash	-20%
Financial Crisis	-30%
Extreme Shock	-50%

The system calculates:

portfolio impact
monetary loss
Historical Crisis Replay

The framework can analyze real market crises.

Implemented scenarios:

COVID Crash

Period:

February 2020 - April 2020

Metrics:

Total Return
Maximum Drawdown
Worst Trading Day
Recovery Time
2022 Rate Shock

Analyzes the impact of rising interest rates and market repricing.

